Supervised Machine Learning (ML)

Supervised Learning is the most commonly used type of Machine Learning.

Definition

Supervised Machine Learning is a type of ML where the model learns from labeled data.

Input (Features) → X
Correct Output (Label/Target) → y

The model learns the relationship between X → y so it can predict the output for new, unseen data.

Example

Hours Studied	Pass/Fail
2	Fail
4	Pass
6	Pass
1	Fail

The model learns from this data and predicts whether a new student will pass or fail.

Workflow of Supervised Learning
Training Data
      ↓
Input (X) + Output (y)
      ↓
Train Model
      ↓
Model Learns Pattern
      ↓
New Input
      ↓
Prediction
Types of Supervised Learning

There are 2 types:

1. Classification

Predicts categories or classes.

Examples:

Spam or Not Spam
Cancer or No Cancer
Fraud or Not Fraud
Cat or Dog
Pass or Fail

Example:

Email	Output
"Win ₹10 lakh"	Spam
"Meeting at 5 PM"	Not Spam

Common Algorithms:

Logistic Regression
Decision Tree
Random Forest
Naive Bayes
Support Vector Machine (SVM)
K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
2. Regression

Predicts continuous numerical values.

Examples:

House Price
Temperature
Salary
Stock Price (with limitations)
Rainfall Amount

Example:

Area (sq.ft)	Price
1000	₹40 Lakh
1200	₹50 Lakh
1500	₹65 Lakh

The model predicts the price of a new house.

Common Algorithms:

Linear Regression
Decision Tree Regressor
Random Forest Regressor
Support Vector Regression (SVR)
Training Process
Step 1: Collect Data

Example:

Age	Salary	Bought Laptop
22	25000	No
35	50000	Yes
40	70000	Yes
Step 2: Split Data

Typically:

Training Set → 80%
Testing Set → 20%
Step 3: Train the Model

The algorithm learns patterns from the training data.

Step 4: Test the Model

Evaluate how well it performs on unseen data.

Step 5: Make Predictions

Example:

Input:

Age = 30
Salary = ₹45,000

Output:

Will Buy Laptop = Yes
Common Algorithms
1. Linear Regression

Used for predicting continuous values.

Example:

House price prediction
2. Logistic Regression

Used for binary classification.

Example:

Pass/Fail
Spam Detection
3. Decision Tree

Makes decisions by asking a series of questions.

Example:

Salary > 50K?
      |
   Yes/No
      |
 Buy / Don't Buy
4. Random Forest

A collection of many decision trees.

Advantages:

Higher accuracy
Less overfitting
Robust to noisy data
5. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)

Predicts based on the labels of the nearest data points.

Example:
If most nearby houses are expensive, the new house is also likely to be expensive.

6. Naive Bayes

Based on Bayes' Theorem.

Used for:

Spam detection
Text classification
Sentiment analysis
7. Support Vector Machine (SVM)

Finds the best boundary (hyperplane) to separate different classes.

Example:

Face recognition
Image classification
Advantages
High accuracy with labeled data.
Easy to evaluate using known outputs.
Widely used in industry.
Many well-established algorithms.
Disadvantages
Requires a large amount of labeled data.
Labeling data can be expensive and time-consuming.
May overfit if not properly regularized.
Performance depends on the quality of the training data.
